''Final Fantasy'' was first re-released for the [[MSX2]] system and was published by [[Microcabin]] in Japan in December 1989.<ref name="msx-mag">{{cite magazine |title=新作ソフト発売スケジュール表 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->  |year= 1989 |magazine=Emu Esu Ekkusu Magajin |script-work=ja:MSXマガジン |trans-work= MSX Magazine |url= https://archive.org/details/MSX_Magazine_1990-01_ASCII_JP/page/n17/mode/2up |language= Japanese |location= Japan |publisher= ASCII Corporation |page= 19 |issue = January 1990 issue |via= The Internet Archive}}</ref> It had access to almost three times as much storage space as the Famicom version but suffered from problems not present in Nintendo's cartridge media, including noticeable loading times. There were also minor graphical upgrades, improved music tracks, and sound effects.

In 1994, ''Final Fantasy I・II'', a compilation of ''Final Fantasy'' and ''Final Fantasy II'', was launched for the Famicom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.play-asia.com/paOS-13-71-bk-49-en-70-pta.html|title=Final Fantasy I & II [pre-owned]|publisher=[[Play-Asia]]|access-date=December 22, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615141434/http://www.play-asia.com/paOS-13-71-bk-49-en-70-pta.html|archive-date=June 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> This version was only released in Japan and had very few graphical updates.

The [[WonderSwan]] Color remake was released in Japan on December 9, 2000,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jp.square-enix.com/game/detail/ff/ |title=ファイナルファンタジー |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |access-date=23 October 2023 |language=ja |trans-title=Final Fantasy |archive-date=January 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240118110518/https://www.jp.square-enix.com/game/detail/ff/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and featured many new graphical changes. The 8-bit graphics of the original Famicom game were updated, battle scenes incorporated full background images, and character and enemy [[sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] were redrawn to look more like the ones from the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]] ''Final Fantasy'' games.<ref name="WSC"/>

In Japan, ''Final Fantasy'' and ''Final Fantasy II'' were re-released both separately and as a combined game for the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]. The collection was released in Japan in 2002 as ''[[Final Fantasy I & II Premium Package]]'' and in Europe and North America in 2003 as ''[[Final Fantasy Origins]]''. This version was similar to the WonderSwan Color remake<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/final-fantasy-origins/reviews/final-fantasy-origins-review-6024755/?tag=summary%3Bread-review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223040518/http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/final-fantasy-origins-review/1900-6024755/|archive-date=December 23, 2015|title=Final Fantasy Origins Review|website=[[GameSpot]]|first=Brad|last=Shoemaker|date=April 8, 2003|access-date=December 23, 2008}}</ref> and featured several changes such as more detailed graphics, a remixed soundtrack, added [[full motion video]] sequences, art galleries of [[Yoshitaka Amano]]'s illustrations, and a memo save function.<ref name="Origins"/> The port was re-released as part of the ''Final Fantasy 25th Anniversary Ultimate Box'' package in December 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://andriasang.com/con2j5/ff_ultimate_box_game_list/ |title=Full Final Fantasy 25th Anniversary Ultimate Box Game List |publisher=Andriasang |author=Gantayat, Anoop |date=August 31, 2012 |access-date=September 2, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060243/http://andriasang.com/con2j5/ff_ultimate_box_game_list/ |archive-date=September 21, 2013}}</ref>

''Final Fantasy I & II: Dawn of Souls'' is, like ''Final Fantasy Origins'', a port of the first two games in the series and was released for the [[Game Boy Advance]] in 2004. The ''Dawn of Souls'' version incorporates various new elements, including four additional dungeons, an updated bestiary, and a few minor changes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/final-fantasy-i-and-ii-dawn-of-souls/videos/final-fantasy-i-and-ii-dawn-of-souls-developer-interview-6114052/|title=Final Fantasy I & II: Dawn of Souls Developer Interview|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=November 29, 2004|access-date=December 22, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922085123/http://www.gamespot.com/final-fantasy-i-and-ii-dawn-of-souls/videos/final-fantasy-i-and-ii-dawn-of-souls-developer-interview-6114052/|archive-date=September 22, 2013}}</ref>

Square Enix released a version of ''Final Fantasy'' for two Japanese mobile phone networks in 2004; a version for [[NTT DoCoMo]] [[Freedom of Mobile Multimedia Access|FOMA]] 900i series was launched in March under the title ''Final Fantasy i''<ref>{{cite web |last=Tsukioka |first=Aki |title=Square Enix to Launch DoCoMo Sites for World-Famous Game Titles |url=http://www.japancorp.net/Article.Asp?Art_ID=6612 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527162523/http://www.japancorp.net/Article.Asp?Art_ID=6612 |archive-date=May 27, 2009 |publisher=Japan Corporate News Network |date=February 24, 2004 |access-date=October 16, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and a subsequent release for [[CDMA2000|CDMA 1X WIN]]-compatible phones was launched in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kddi.com/english/corporate/news_release/2004/0712/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040810001050/http://www.kddi.com/english/corporate/news_release/2004/0712/index.html|archive-date=August 10, 2004|title=KDDI Announces Three New CDMA 1X WIN Models|publisher=[[KDDI]]|access-date=December 23, 2008}}</ref> Another version was released for [[SoftBank]] [[Yahoo!]] Keitai phones on July 3, 2006.<ref>{{cite web | title=ファイナルファンタジー for MOBILE | publisher=[[Square Enix]] | url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/mobile/ff/ | language=ja | access-date=October 16, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020203051/http://www.square-enix.co.jp/mobile/ff/ | archive-date=October 20, 2012 | url-status=live}}</ref> The games have more refined graphics compared to the original 8-bit game, but not as advanced as many of the later console and handheld ports.

Square Enix planned to release this version for North American mobile phones in 2006,<ref>{{cite web | title=Square Enix to Showcase All Encompassing Line-up at E3 2006 | publisher=[[Square Enix]] | url=http://www.square-enix.com/na/company/press/2006/0424/ | date=April 24, 2006 | access-date=October 16, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207221923/http://www.square-enix.com/na/company/press/2006/0424/ | archive-date=February 7, 2012 | url-status=live}}</ref> but it was delayed to 2010 and released in collaboration with [[Namco]]. It retains the game difficulty and "spell level"-based magic system from the original Famicom version. Other elements such as updated graphics, spell names, and monster names are borrowed from the [[Game Boy Advance]] / [[WonderSwan]] Color versions, not including the additional dungeons, monsters and items present in the GBA version. Game data is saved as in the original Famicom version (by using Tent, Sleeping Bag, and Cottage or by going into an inn), but there are now three save game slots and a "Temporary Save" option available in the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.namcogames.com/mobile/final-fantasy_8603.html |title=Namco Games - Final Fantasy mobile |publisher=[[Namco]] |access-date=August 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626115736/http://www.namcogames.com/mobile/final-fantasy_8603.html |archive-date=June 26, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

For the 20th anniversary of ''Final Fantasy'', Square Enix remade ''Final Fantasy'' and ''Final Fantasy II'' for the [[PlayStation Portable]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/final-fantasy-remakes-coming-psp|title=Final Fantasy Remakes Coming to PSP|website=[[1UP.com]]|first=Jonathan|last=Lumb|date=January 17, 2007|access-date=December 23, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524021451/http://www.1up.com/news/final-fantasy-remakes-coming-psp|archive-date=May 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The games were released in Japan and North America in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.square-enix.com/na/company/press/2007/0626/|title=Square Enix ships remastered edition of Final Fantasy to retail|publisher=[[Square Enix]]|date=June 26, 2007|access-date=October 16, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055850/http://www.square-enix.com/na/company/press/2007/0626/|archive-date=September 21, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and in European territories in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/final-fantasy-anniversary-edition/related/platform/psp/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125215425/http://www.gamespot.com/final-fantasy-anniversary-edition/related/platform/psp/ |archive-date=January 25, 2012 |title=Final Fantasy Anniversary Edition for PSP |access-date=October 16, 2008 |website=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> The PSP version features higher-resolution 2D graphics, full motion video sequences, a remixed soundtrack, and a new dungeon as well as the bonus dungeons from ''Dawn of Souls''. The script is the same as in the ''Dawn of Souls'' version, aside from the new dungeon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.psp.gamespy.com/playstation-portable/final-fantasy-i-/782716p1.html|title=Final Fantasy Preview|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|first=Nakamura|last=Masae|date=April 23, 2007|access-date=December 22, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922095045/http://uk.psp.gamespy.com/playstation-portable/final-fantasy-i-/782716p1.html|archive-date=September 22, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> This version was later released for the Nintendo 3DS (on the Japanese eShop only) with the addition of Stereoscopic 3D.

Square Enix released the original NES version of the game on the [[Wii]]'s [[Virtual Console]] service in Japan on May 26, 2009,<ref>{{cite web|title=VC ファイナルファンタジー|trans-title=VC Final Fantasy|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_ff/index.html|publisher=Nintendo|access-date=October 5, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525193854/http://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_ff/index.html|archive-date=May 25, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> in North America on October 5<ref>{{cite web|title=Discover New Worlds, Hidden Words and the First ''Final Fantasy''|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/c4tMRvn7hyMKidz4qH-aw4rwS6d9j7M9|publisher=Nintendo of America|date=October 5, 2009|access-date=October 5, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091008101448/http://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/c4tMRvn7hyMKidz4qH-aw4rwS6d9j7M9|archive-date=October 8, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> and in the PAL region as an import on May 7, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/games/nes/final_fantasy|title=Final Fantasy|author=Nintendo Life|work=Nintendo Life|access-date=April 17, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411064552/http://www.nintendolife.com/games/nes/final_fantasy|archive-date=April 11, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>

