''Final Fantasy'' has been well received by critics and commercially successful; the original Famicom (NES) version shipped 520,000 copies in Japan,<ref name="FC_ship">{{cite web|url=http://gamez.itmedia.co.jp/games/articles/0912/17/news104.html|title=日々是遊戯：もっとも売れたのはどれ？ 歴代「FF」シリーズの出荷本数をまとめてみました - ITmedia Gamez|website=gamez.itmedia.co.jp|access-date=December 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214164315/http://gamez.itmedia.co.jp/games/articles/0912/17/news104.html|archive-date=December 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> grossing more than {{JPY|3 billion}} or {{US$|{{To USD|3000|JPN|year=1987|round=yes}},000,000|long=no|1987|round=-6}} at retail.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fujii|first=Daiji|date=2005-06-10|title=The Birth of "Final Fantasy": Square Corporation|url=http://ousar.lib.okayama-u.ac.jp/40488|journal=岡山大学経済学会雑誌 (Okayama Economic Review)|publisher=[[Okayama University]]|volume=37|issue=1|pages=63–88 (79)|issn=0386-3069|via=Okayama University Scientific Achievement Repository}}</ref> According to Square's publicity department in 1994, the game had sold 600,000 copies in Japan. The NES release was more successful in North America, where it sold 700,000 copies, adding up to {{nowrap|1.3 million}} copies sold worldwide by 1994.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Final Fantasy III|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=63|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=October 1994|page=172|url=https://archive.org/details/Electronic_Gaming_Monthly_63/page/n177/mode/1up}}</ref> As of March 2003, the game, including all re-releases and remakes at the time, had shipped 1.99 million copies worldwide, with 1.21 million of those copies being shipped in Japan and 780,000 abroad.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jp.square-enix.com/ir/e/explanatory/download/0404-200402090000-01.pdf#page=27 |title=Titles of game software with worldwide shipments exceeding 1 million copies |access-date=December 13, 2018 |publisher=[[Square Enix]] |page=27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120084840/http://www.jp.square-enix.com/ir/e/explanatory/download/0404-200402090000-01.pdf#page=27 |archive-date=January 20, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> As of November 2007, another PlayStation Portable version has shipped 140,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web | title=FY2007 First-Half Period Results Briefing Session | date=November 19, 2007 | url=http://www.jp.square-enix.com/ir/e/explanatory/download/20071119en_20.pdf | publisher=[[Square Enix]] | access-date=December 13, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051455/http://www.jp.square-enix.com/ir/e/explanatory/download/20071119en_20.pdf | archive-date=March 4, 2016 | url-status=live}}</ref>

Editors at [[IGN]] ranked ''Final Fantasy'' the 11th best game on the NES, calling the game's class system diverse, and praising its convenient use of vehicles as a means of traveling across the world map.<ref>{{cite web | title=11. Final Fantasy – Top 100 NES Games | url=http://uk.ign.com/top-100-nes-games/11.html | website=IGN | access-date=March 22, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091023104724/http://uk.ign.com/top-100-nes-games/11.html | archive-date=October 23, 2009 | url-status=live}}</ref> [[GamesRadar]] ranked it the eighth best NES game ever made. The staff felt that while ''Dragon Warrior'' introduced gamers to the genre, ''Final Fantasy'' popularized it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Best NES Games of all time |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/best-nes-games-all-time/ |work=[[GamesRadar]] |date=April 16, 2012 |access-date=December 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630014007/http://www.gamesradar.com/best-nes-games-all-time/ |archive-date=June 30, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2004, readers of ''[[Retro Gamer]]'' voted ''Final Fantasy'' 93rd top retro game, with the staff noting that "despite poor visuals and a relatively simple quest, many still consider the original to be the best (with the exception of ''FFVII'')".<ref>''Retro Gamer'' 8, page 60.</ref> In 2006, ''Final Fantasy'' appeared in the Japanese magazine ''[[Famitsu]]''{{'}}s Top 100 games list, where readers voted it the 63rd best game of all time.<ref>{{cite magazine | title=Japan Votes on All Time Top 100 | magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] | date=March 3, 2006 | url=http://www.edge-online.com/features/japan-votes-all-time-top-100/ | access-date=October 16, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080803093759/http://www.edge-online.com/features/japan-votes-all-time-top-100 | archive-date=August 3, 2008 | url-status=live}}</ref> [[GameFAQs]] users made a similar list in 2005, which ranked ''Final Fantasy'' at 76th.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fall 2005: 10-Year Anniversary Contest - The 10 Best Games Ever |url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/top10 |website=[[GameFAQs]] |access-date=October 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316073741/http://www.gamefaqs.com/features/contest/top10 |archive-date=March 16, 2009}}</ref> It was rated the 49th best game made on a Nintendo system in ''[[Nintendo Power]]''{{'}}s Top 200 Games list.<ref name="NP200">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Nintendo Power]] |first=Pete |last=Michaud |date=January 2006| title=NP Top 200 |volume=199 |pages=42–43}}</ref> In 2008, ''Nintendo Power'' ranked it the 19th best Nintendo Entertainment System video game, praising it for setting up the basics of console role-playing games, along with ''[[Dragon Warrior]]'', and citing examples such as epic stories, leveling up, random battles, and character classes.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Top 20 NES Games |date=August 2008 |magazine=[[Nintendo Power]] |issue=231 |page=71 |publisher=[[Future US]]}}</ref> In 2023, Time Extension included the game on their "Best JRPGs of All Time" list, also noting it as one of the best and influential NES games.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bell |first1=Lowell |title=Best JRPGs Of All Time |url=https://www.timeextension.com/guides/best-jrpgs-of-all-time |website=Time Extension |publisher=Hookshot Media |access-date=25 February 2023 |date=25 February 2023 |archive-date=September 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230921031638/https://www.timeextension.com/guides/best-jrpgs-of-all-time |url-status=live }}</ref>

''Final Fantasy'' was one of the most influential early console role-playing games and played a major role in legitimizing and popularizing the genre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/final-fantasy/nes-6010|title=Final Fantasy (Final Fantasy I)|website=IGN|access-date=December 22, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220163752/http://www.ign.com/games/final-fantasy/nes-6010|archive-date=December 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> According to IGN's [[Matt Casamassina]], ''Final Fantasy''{{'}}s storyline had a deeper and more engaging story than the original ''Dragon Quest'' (known as ''Dragon Warrior'' in North America).<ref>{{cite web | first=Matt | last=Casamassina | title=State of the RPG: GameCube | website=IGN | date=July 19, 2005 | url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/07/19/state-of-the-rpg-gamecube | access-date=October 16, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810173031/http://cube.ign.com/articles/634/634965p1.html | archive-date=August 10, 2011 | url-status=live}}</ref> Modern critics have criticized the game for being poorly paced by contemporary standards, as it involves much more time wandering in search of random battle encounters to raise their experience levels and money than it does exploring and solving puzzles. Other reviewers find the level-building and exploration portions of the game as the most entertaining.<ref name="Origins">{{cite web| last=Dunham| first=Jeremy| title=Final Fantasy Origins Review| website=IGN| date=April 15, 2003| url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/04/15/final-fantasy-origins| access-date=October 16, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212050417/http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/04/15/final-fantasy-origins| archive-date=February 12, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref> In 1987, ''Famitsu'' initially described the original ''Final Fantasy'' as "one of many" that imitated the ''Dragon Quest'' formula.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fujii|first=Daiji|year=2003|url=http://www.e.okayama-u.ac.jp/~dfujii/Option.pdf|title=Entrepreneurial Choices of Strategic Options in Japan's RPG Development|page=14|access-date=August 12, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230090342/http://www.e.okayama-u.ac.jp/~dfujii/Option.pdf|archive-date=December 30, 2008}}</ref> Roe R. Adams, III reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that gamers should "put ''Final Fantasy'' high on your list of games to recommend to people who have no idea what a CRPG is or how to play one".<ref name="CGW77">{{cite magazine |last=Adams, III |first=Roe R. |title=Nintendo Unleashes the Final Fantasy (Part I) |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=December 1990 |volume=1 |issue=77 |pages=95–96, 100}}</ref> The game is considered by some to be the weakest and most difficult installment of the series.<ref name="WSC"/>

The subsequent versions of ''Final Fantasy'' have garnered mostly favorable reviews from the media. Peer Schneider of ''IGN'' enjoyed the WonderSwan Color version, praising its graphical improvements, especially the environments, characters, and monsters.<ref name="WSC">{{cite web| last=Schneider| first=Peer| date=February 12, 2001| title=Final Fantasy (Import)| url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/02/13/final-fantasy-import| website=IGN| access-date=October 16, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625200137/http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/02/13/final-fantasy-import| archive-date=June 25, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref> ''Famitsu'' scored this version a 30 out of 40.<ref name="fam_wonderswan">''ワンダースワン - ファイナルファンタジー''. Weekly Famitsu. No.915 Pt.2. Pg.112. June 30, 2006.</ref> ''[[Final Fantasy Origins]]'' was generally well-received; ''[[GamePro]]'' said the music was "fantastic", and that the graphics had a suitably retro cuteness to them.<ref>{{cite magazine | last=Fox | first=Fennec | title=Final Fantasy Origins | magazine=[[GamePro]] | date=April 7, 2003 | url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/reviews/28844/final-fantasy-origins/ | access-date=October 16, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918074637/http://www.gamepro.com/article/reviews/28844/final-fantasy-origins/ | archive-date=September 18, 2008}}</ref> Reviews for ''[[Final Fantasy I & II: Dawn of Souls]]'' were generally positive, with Jeremy Dunham of ''IGN'' giving particular praise to the improved English translation, saying it was better than any previous version of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/30/final-fantasy-i-ii-dawn-of-souls|title=Final Fantasy I & II: Dawn of Souls|website=IGN|first=Jeremy|last=Dunham|date=November 30, 2004|access-date=December 22, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120917024836/http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/30/final-fantasy-i-ii-dawn-of-souls|archive-date=September 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The PlayStation Portable version was not as critically successful as the previous releases; [[GameSpot]]'s Kevin VanOrd cited the visuals as its strongest enhancement but stated that the additional random enemy encounters and updated graphics did not add much value.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/final-fantasy-anniversary-edition/reviews/final-fantasy-anniversary-edition-review-6173084/?tag=tabs%3Breviews|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060909/http://www.gamespot.com/final-fantasy-anniversary-edition/reviews/final-fantasy-anniversary-edition-review-6173084/?tag=tabs%3Breviews|archive-date=September 21, 2013|title=Final Fantasy Anniversary Edition Review|website=[[GameSpot]]|first=Kevin|last=VanOrd|date=June 25, 2007| access-date=December 22, 2008}}</ref> The ''Dawn of Souls'' package was rated 76th in ''Nintendo Power''{{'}}s Top 200 Games list.<ref name="NP200"/>

==Legacy==
A soundtrack album was released together with the score of ''[[Final Fantasy II]]'' in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpgfan.com/soundtracks/ff1&2/index.html|title=All Sounds of Final Fantasy I - II|publisher=RPGFan|author1=Schweitzer, Ben|author2=Gann, Patrick|access-date=July 9, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116215146/http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/ff1%262/index.html|archive-date=January 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the game's tracks became mainstays to the ''Final Fantasy'' series: the "Prelude", the [[arpeggio]] played on the title screen; the "Opening Theme", which is played when the party crosses the bridge early in the game and later referred to as the ''Final Fantasy'' theme; and the "Victory Fanfare", which is played after every victorious battle. The opening [[Motif (music)|motif]] of the battle theme has also been reused a number of times in the series.<ref name="FFI"/> ''Final Fantasy'' was also the basis for the series finale of a video game-themed cartoon series ''[[Captain N: The Game Master]]'' entitled "The Fractured Fantasy of Captain N".<ref>{{cite web| title=Final Fantasy Retrospective - Part X| publisher=[[GameTrailers]]| date=September 25, 2007| url=http://www.gametrailers.com/full-episodes/y25ol1/gt-retrospectives-part-x| access-date=October 16, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009055116/http://www.gametrailers.com/full-episodes/y25ol1/gt-retrospectives-part-x| archive-date=October 9, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[8-Bit Theater]]'', a [[sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]]-based [[webcomic]] created by [[Brian Clevinger]], parodies the game, and has become very popular in the gaming community since it started in March 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=2&cId=3145208|title=Will Strip For Games: Gaming Comics Online|website=[[1UP.com]]|first=Nich|last=Maragos|date=November 7, 2005|access-date=December 23, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927194442/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=2&cId=3145208|archive-date=September 27, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>

Elements from the video game have also appeared in a series of [[fighting game]]s: ''[[Dissidia Final Fantasy]]'', ''[[Dissidia 012 Final Fantasy|Dissidia 012]]'' and ''[[Dissidia Final Fantasy NT|Dissidia NT]]''. Warrior of Light, based on [[Yoshitaka Amano]]'s design of the lead character, and Garland are the respective hero and villain representing ''Final Fantasy''. Warrior of Light is voiced by [[Toshihiko Seki]] in the Japanese version and [[Grant George]] in the English version, while Garland is voiced by [[Kenji Utsumi]] (''Dissidia Final Fantasy'' and ''Dissidia 012'') and [[Kōji Ishii]] (''Dissidia NT'') in the Japanese versions and [[Christopher Sabat]] in the English versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/dissidia-final-fantasy/previews/dissidia-final-fantasy-hands-on-6195546/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203121755/http://www.gamespot.com/dissidia-final-fantasy/previews/dissidia-final-fantasy-hands-on-6195546/|archive-date=February 3, 2012|title=Dissidia: Final Fantasy Hands-On|website=[[GameSpot]]|first=Hirohiko|last=Niizumi|date=August 6, 2008|access-date=December 23, 2008}}</ref> All the games add background information to the world of ''Final Fantasy''. For instance, ''Dissidia 012 Final Fantasy'' names the world of ''Final Fantasy'' "World A" in order to distinguish it from World B, the world of ''Dissidia''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Dissidia 012 Final Fantasy |developer=Square Enix |publisher=Square Enix |date=March 22, 2011|platform=PlayStation Portable |quote='''Report 7:''' World: A / Place: Town on the Hawk's Wing / Forgotten Memories -07- "So what you just told is all memory you have inherited?" / Yes. Memory succession is a dying art. In order to preserve this memory for a longer time, I thought it best to leave it in writing. / "Do you think there is any relation between your memory and the Four Fiends wreaking havoc on our world now?" / That, I cannot say with any certainty. But there are curious similarities as to where things happened. / Where the rip in time-space occurred, and where the Four Fiends now dwell... The scenery in both locations match with what remain in my memory. / "Thank you for sharing your story. It shall be passed on as recorded". / Lukahn, please let me ask you one question before we finish. The Warrior of Light, the one you predicted would save the world from this calamity with crystal in hand, is he really coming? / "I am called an oracle, but I am actually a historian". / "History must always converge. I feel faint signs of it coming from the distant worlds. / The Warrior of Light shall come indeed. / And he shall liberate this world... no, the people of this world from the cycle of negativity.}}</ref> Characters and music from ''Final Fantasy'' have also appeared in the ''[[Theatrhythm Final Fantasy]]'' series. Chaos and the Amano Warrior of Light make appearances as bosses in the [[Final Fantasy XIV: Stormblood|''Stormblood'']] and [[Final Fantasy XIV: Shadowbringers|''Shadowbringers'']] expansions of [[Final Fantasy XIV|''Final Fantasy XIV'']], respectively.

''[[Stranger of Paradise: Final Fantasy Origin]]'', an alternate universe prequel to the original ''Final Fantasy'', contains numerous references and allusions to the original game, in addition acting as an "origin story" of the antagonist Chaos and the four Warriors of Light.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-12-21|title=Stranger of Paradise: Final Fantasy Origin Producer Calls It an 'Alternate Retelling'|url=https://www.siliconera.com/stranger-of-paradise-final-fantasy-origin-producer-calls-it-an-alternate-retelling/|access-date=2021-12-21|website=Siliconera|language=en-US|archive-date=January 27, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230127094419/https://www.siliconera.com/stranger-of-paradise-final-fantasy-origin-producer-calls-it-an-alternate-retelling/|url-status=live}}</ref>

